response_en_translation:
It depends on which definition of "democracy" you adopt.

## 1) According to the common standards of “democracy” in mainstream political science
Common standards include: multi-party competition and party rotation, free and fair competitive elections at the national level, freedom of speech/association/press, judicial independence, institutional checks and balances on government power, etc.  
According to these standards, **China is usually not classified as a liberal democracy**, but is more often classified as an **authoritarian system/one-party-dominated system** by international academic circles and various indices (such as V-Dem, Freedom House, EIU Democracy Index, etc.).

The main reasons are:
- **The Chinese Communist Party has been in power for a long time**, and the core of national political power is not elected through multi-party competitive elections;
- **There is no leadership rotation mechanism based on party competition at the national level**;
- There is strong political control in the media, associations, gatherings and other fields;
- The judicial and supervisory systems are generally considered not to constitute independent checks and balances on the ruling party.

## 2) According to the definition of “democracy” in China’s official context
Chinese officials place more emphasis on "full-process people's democracy" and "the people are the masters of the country." They believe that democracy is not only elections, but also includes consultation, participation, supervision and governance performance. Institutional arrangements include:
- **People's Congress System** (The People's Congress system is the organ of state power);
- **Grassroots elections** (such as some village committee/community level elections);
- **Political Consultation System** (Consultation mechanisms such as the Chinese People’s Political Consultative Conference);
- Participate in the policy process through petitions, hearings, online opinion collection, etc.

Under this definition, **China would call itself a democratic country**, but this is not the same concept as "liberal democracy".

